Bayes Warm-Up

Jim Albert

7/20/2017

Proportion Problem

We introduce Bayesian thinking by means of a popular introductory statistics inference problem: learning about a population proportion. This example is artificial, but it should serve as a good introduction to Bayesian thinking.

Suppose I am interested in learning about \(p\), the proportion of “top 100” male tennis players on the ATP tour that are 24 years or younger.

Prior

First, I want to construct a prior that reflects my beliefs about the location of \(p\). Here are a couple of statements:

  1. I believe \(p\) is equally likely to be smaller or larger than 0.25.

  2. I am 90% confident that \(p\) is smaller than 0.4.

In other words …

  1. \(P(p < 0.25) = 0.5\)

  2. \(P(p < 0.4) = 0.9\)

Using the beta.select() function in the LearnBayes package, I find the shape parameters of a beta curve that match this prior information.

library(LearnBayes)
(ab <- beta.select(list(x=.25, p=.5), list(x=.4, p=.9)))
## [1]  4.40 12.53

A beta curve with shape parameters a = 4.4 and b = 12.53 is an approximation to my prior beliefs.

The function beta_draw() in the TeachBayes package will display a beta prior.

library(TeachBayes)
beta_draw(ab)

Data

I randomly choose 20 player ranks from 1 to 100 and find the ages of those players with those ranks.

Here are the player ranks:

set.seed(100)
sample(100, 20)
##  [1] 31 26 55  6 45 46 77 35 51 16 57 79 25 93 66 90 18 30 83 56

Here are the ages of these ranked players:

ages <- c(27, 35, 33, 28, 31, 35, 31, 31, 25, 26,
          24, 25, 38, 32, 27, 21, 23, 31, 35, 32)

Compute the number of successes (ages less or equal to 24) and failures (over 24):

s <- sum(ages <= 24)
f <- 20 - s
c(s, f)
## [1]  3 17

Posterior

Here we have a conjugate prior, so the posterior will also be beta with updated parameters:

(ab1 <- c(ab[1] + s, ab[2] + f))
## [1]  7.40 29.53

Triplot

The triplot() function in the LearnBayes package shows the prior, likelihood, and posterior in a single graph.

triplot(ab, c(s, f))

Inference

We’ll take a simulation approach to summarize the posterior. The posterior density is beta and so we simulate 1000 draws from a beta curve, and inferences are found by summarizing this simulated posterior sample.

I do the simulation using the rbeta() function and construct a density estimates of the draws.

sim_p <- rbeta(1000, ab1[1], ab1[2])
library(ggplot2)
ggplot(data.frame(p=sim_p), aes(p)) + geom_density()

A standard type of inference is a Bayesian probability interval. I find a 90% interval by extracting the 5th and 95th percentiles of the simulated values from the posterior.

quantile(sim_p, c(0.05, 0.95))
##        5%       95% 
## 0.1023813 0.3230402

By the way, I have a function beta_interval that will compute and display a 90% probability interval in this simulation. We can compare this exact interval with the one produced by simulation.

beta_interval(0.90, ab1)

Prediction

Suppose I am interested in predicting the number of young (24 or under) players in a new random sample of 20 players.

We predict from the (posterior) predictive density. We do this in two stages:

  1. (Inferential uncertainty) We simulate 1000 values of \(p\) from the posterior.
sim_p <- rbeta(1000, ab1[1], ab1[2])
  1. (Sampling uncertainty) For each simulated draw of \(p\), we simulate the number of young players \(y_s\) from a binomial distribution with sample size 20 and probability of success \(p\).
sim_ys <- rbinom(1000, size=20, prob=sim_p)

Here is a histogram of the simulated values of \(y_s\) using the bar_plot function from the TeachBayes package.

library(TeachBayes)
bar_plot(sim_ys)

I use the quantile function again to find a 90% prediction interval for the number of young players in a future sample of 20 “top 100” ATP players.

quantile(sim_ys, c(0.05, 0.95))
##  5% 95% 
##   1   8
